column85: Cont1 Valve Or Device Fail Ind
column168: Description Of Events
column169: Recommendations Actions Taken

column168: PROPANE BOBTAIL LEFT THE ROAD AND ROLLED ONTO IT’S LEFT SIDE. DRIVER WAS NOT INJURED. THE BOBTAIL SUFFERED DAMAGE. HAD TO FLARE 2400 GALLONS OF PRODUCT. THE DRIVER TOOK HIS EYES OFF THE ROAD WHEN HE THOUGHT HE HEARD SOMETHING FAIL IN THE CAB OF THE TRUCK AND THE RIGHT-HAND TIRES WENT OFF THE ROAD, AND THE TRUCK ROLLED ON ITS LEFT SIDE.  SMALL PROPANE LEAKS IN DAMAGED PIPING PREVENTED THE VEHICLE FROM BEING MOVED OFF SITE UNTIL ALL PRODUCT WAS BURNED OFF WITH A CONTROLLED BURN ESTIMATE THAT LESS THAN 10 GALLONS OF PROPANE VAPOR LEAKED AND WAS DISPERSED INTO THE ATOMSPHERE, A FLARE WAS SET UP ABOUT 300FT UPWIND OF THE CRASH SITE, THE CONTROLLED BURN LOWERED THE PRESSURE IN THE CONTAINER SLOWING ANY LEAKS CONSIDERABLY.  A SMALL AMOUNT OF DIESEL AND ENGINE OIL LEAKED INTO A DITCH WA CLEANED UP BY HEPACO OF CHARLOTTE, NC.
column169: DRIVER AT FAULT, EMPLOYMENT WAS TERMINATED.

column42: AMINES, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, N.O.S. OR POLYAMINES, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, N.O.S.
column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE IN TRANSIT, A SINGLE-VEHICLE, ROLLOVER ACCIDENT OCCURRED. THE CHESTERFIELD FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE SITE AND CONDUCTED AN INVESTIGATION OF THE SITE AND INSPECTED THE VEHICLE. FIRST CALL ENVIRONMENTAL WAS RETAINED BY SLAY TRANSPORTATION TO CONDUCT CLEANUP ON SITE AND ASSIST WITH PRODUCT TRANSFER. DURING THE PRODUCT TRANSFER APPROXIMATELY SEVEN (7) GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT RELEASE ON TO THE ASPHALT – THIS FREE PRODUCT WAS RESIDUAL FROM THE HOSE USED IN THE TRANSFER. INVESTIGATION BY THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND FIRST CALL ENVIRONMENTAL COULD NOT CONFIRM THAT ANY RELEASE OF FREE PRODUCT OCCURRED DURING THE ACCIDENT. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED IN CONNECTION WITH THIS INCIDENT. VIRGINIA ROUTE 10 WAS CLOSED FOR APPROXIMATELY ONE (1) HOUR DUE TO THE ACCIDENT.
column169: SLAY TRANSPORTATION WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND REINFORCE SAFE HANDLING PROCEDURES AND DRIVER SAFETY TO ALL PERSONNEL.

column168: APPROXIMATELY 1400 GALLON OF FERRIC CHLORIDE SOLUTION SPILLED AS PVS TRANSPORTATION WAS MAKING A DELIVERY TO THE CITY OF CARO WASTE WATER TREATMENT PLANT. THE SPILL OCCURRED ON 1/8/2018, AT APPROXIMATELY 12:00 PM. THE FERRIC CHLORIDE SOLUTION SPILLED ONTO THE COLUMBUS ROAD PAVEMENT, AS THE TANKER WAS ENTERING THE FACILITY, AND A PAVED ASPHALT AREA. WITHIN THE CARO TREATMENT PLANT. THE LEAK WAS FROM THE BOTTOM SUMP FLANGE OF THE CARGO TANK FROM HOLE OF APPROX. 1 ½ X 1”.  AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE WAS IMMEDIATELY INITIATED BY THE DRIVER WHEN THE RELEASE WAS DISCOVERED BY A CITIZEN. THE TANKER WAS ISOLATED, THE SPILL CONTAINED BY SAND DIKE, THE LEAK WAS CAPTURED INTO A SPILL CONTAINMENT + PUMPED.
column169: CORRECTIVE ACTION IMPLEMENTED A RETURN TO SERVICE VERIFICATION CHECKLIST. TO INCLUDE THE REVIEW OF VALVES, PIPING, FLANGES ETC. TO CONFIRM THE CORRECT MATERIAL OF CONSTRUCTION IS IN PLACE. TRAINING FOR INSPECTORS OF VESSEL ON PART 180, SUB-PART E. QUALIFICATIONS AND MAINTENANCE OF CARGO TANKS.

column168: MVP TRUCKING'S VEHICLE WAS HEADING EASTBOUND ON HIGHWAY 54 AFTER PICKING UP A LOAD OF CRUDE OIL. PRELIMINARY REPORT INDICATE THIS ACCIDENT WAS CAUSED BY THE DRIVER OF THE CHEVY PICKUP. THE CHEVY PICKUP WAS HEADING SOUTH ON 125TH RD IN KINGSDOWN KS. IT APPEARS THE PICKUP PULLED OUT FROM A STOP SIGN WITHOUT LOOKING BOTH WAYS, MVP'S DRIVER SWERVED RIGHT TO AVOID THE ACCIDENT, BUT THE TWO VEHICLES COLLIDED. MVP'S VEHICLE WAS COMPLETELY ON FIRE WHEN POLICE ARRIVED ON THE SCENE. POLICE AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENTS DECIDED TO BLOCK ENTRY AND LET THE TRUCK/TRAILER BURN DUE TO IT BEING A CONTAINED INCIDENT. MVP WAS UNABLE TO DOWNLOAD THE ECM DATA FROM MVP'S TRUCK DUE TO THE DAMAGE TO THE VEHICLE. THE VEHICLE AND TRAILER HAVE BEEN DEEMED TOTAL LOSSES FROM OUR INSURANCE COMPANY. PHOTOS HAVE BEEN ATTACHED. A DOWNLOAD OF THE AIRBAG CONTROL MODULE IN THE CHEVY PICKUP SHOWED HE WAS GOING 14 MPH AT THE TIME OF THE ACCIDENT. THE POLICE REPORT NUMBER HAS BEEN ADDED TO THIS REPORT. ALL DAMAGE VALUES HAVE BEEN UPDATED AS WELL.
column169: PRELIMINARY REPORTS ARE SHOWING OUR DRIVER DID EVERYTHING HE COULD TO AVOID THE ACCIDENT. WE WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN OUR DRIVERS ON DRIVER SAFETY PROCEDURES.

column168: On 02/05/2018, a Federal Railroad Administration Hazardous Materials Inspector took exception to tank car UTLX 644099 as having loose closures and product adhering to the exterior of the package. On 02/06/2018 at 0825, a CSX authorized contractor in the CSXT Demmler Yard discovered UTLX 644099, a loaded tank car of Environmentally Hazardous Substances, Liquid, N.O.S., leaking from the manway. The car was isolated and the FRA, NRC, and Shipper were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2018-0206-00044). HEPACO, LLC, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a less than hand tight vacuum relief device. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's contact, Mr. Joseph Eskra of The Lubrizol Corporation, phone 216-447-6374. Contractor personnel secured the vacuum relief device and removed all spilled material. The leak was secured and the car was released for transportation. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 is not required.    Cause Code:444  NARRI:110

column168: shipment built up & loaded on 96"airline pallet. Set up for transport via roller bed trailer to aircraft. After successfully loading pallet via automated roller system on to the truck the driver pulled away before securing the pallet on the trailer. The pallet rolled back off the truck hitting the pavement causing the damage and rupture to the machine causing the release of the Liquid helium gas and subsequent incident.
column169: As the damage was caused by a 3rd party contracted to transport the cargo from the cargo facility to the aircraft it was first suggested that the driver causing the accident be sent for a drug/alcohol test as is the airlines procedure when an incident occurs. At this point it's unclear if the transport company did so. Also suggested all drivers and staff are retrained in all transport safety procedures when transporting any type of cargo via motorized vehicle. In  addition the airline staff are all being reminded to stop any action if they feel it is deemed to be a threat to safety of the cargo or staff.

column168: While offloading at the disposal facility’s 10 day storage area, the driver lifted the roll-container and the winch cable on the truck broke, releasing the container from the truck and it slid off the unit, landing hard on the ground. The force of this impact allowed for some of the roll-off container’s contents to be released onto the ground. Concrete was the only surface impacted; no water ways, storm drains or soil were contaminated. In proper personnel protective equipment, facility personnel were able to remediate the area and dispose of the contents of the container without further incident. The released amount was below state regulatory requirements, thus no state notification was made.
column169: An investigation was launched into the maintenance of the unit and it was determined that an overweight box previously put onto this truck and then taken off due to the weight, compromised the winch cable. The driver was re-trained on thoroughly inspection components of the truck, to include the lifting mechanisms. Key points of the incident were shared with the branch and region.

column168: On February 2, 2018 at approximately 16:30 hours Luke Sims was contacted by Oscar Franco to instruct him to deliver two totes of KDO-5248S to the Pioneer Germania Horizontal Battery.     Luke informed Franco that he was out of hours for the day but could make the delivery Saturday.     At approximately 17:00 hours Skyler Rogers contacted Luke and instructed him to deliver the products knowing that Luke was out of hours for the day.    Luke loaded 8 drums onto trailer #75 and completed the first delivery at approximately 21:30 hours, travelled back to the Clariant yard and loaded two totes of KDO-5248S, approximately 550 gallons, then departed for the final delivery.    Shortly after travelling onto FM-307 Luke felt and observed the trailer swaying, applied the truck brakes, and the trailer collided into the rear of the truck. (NOTE: the trailer coupler had come loose from the trailer hitch on the truck and was being suspended by the safety chains) The impact ruptured one of the totes which spilled approximately 25 gallons of KDO-5248S (NOTE: No reportable quantities released) onto the highway.     Luke contacted Skyler Rogers and informed him that his trailer had come off his truck. Skyler and Landon Gone arrived on scene and noticed the trailer tongue under the rear of the truck and one of the totes was releasing chemical onto the ground. Skyler contacted CHEMTREC and instructed Oscar Franco to go to the Clariant yard to pick up an empty tote so the contents of the damaged tote could be transferred.    Brian Tennis, Midland Fire Department, CHEMTREC and EH&S Remediation was notified.    Luke, Brian Tennis, Skyler Rogers and Landon Gone remained on scene until the site was remediated.    Luke was issued the following citations (TX53K00VBALS) from Texas Department of Public Safety:  • Failure to mark ID number on bulk package – no 1993 on trailer or placards  • Improper description of mixture (technical names) – no technical names  • Incorrect packing group listed – has packing group III listed when it’s a packing group II  • Failure to enter basic description in proper sequence – industry name listed first, packing group listed before hazard class  • Improper description of hazardous material on shipping paper – no UN# listed  • IBC manufacturer markings – none on 1 tote  • IBC protection test dates – none on 1 tote  • Leaking/release of hazardous material package – leaking due to damage    During Wade Smith’s interview with Luke Sims, Luke was asked if he had used the truck for personal use and Luke stated, “No”. Luke stated that he had used the truck numerous times pulling trailers and never had an issue.    An investigation of the trailer ball on the truck showed that it was 2 inch ball. All of the 16 foot utility conversion trailers are equipped with a 2 5/16 coupler hitch and the standard delivery trailers are equipped with a 2 inch coupler hitch.
column169: Perform a thorough JSA  Perform a thorough pre-trip inspection of the vehicle and trailer  Improve employee ability to recognize existing or potential hazardous conditions  Review job procedures for hazard avoidance  Send out a Safety Alert

column168: JOSEPH KRUEGER RECEIVED THE CALL TO RESPOND TO THE LEAKING PACKAGE OUTSIDE OF DOOR 141 ON PD-1, AFTER DONNING APRON, BOOTS, GLOVES, AND GOGGLES JOSEPH RESPONDED WITH HIS SPILL CART TO THE CALL. HE ARRIVED TO FIND THE WET AND POSSIBLY LEAKING PACKAGE ON THE GROUND UNDER THE ROLLERS OF DOOR 141 NEAR THE SUPERVISOR DESK, HE PROCEEDED TO CORDON OFF AN AREA OF 15 FEET AND RETRIEVED HIS DECISION TREE, AFTER WHICH READING THROUGH, HE UNDERSTOOD THAT CORROSIVE LIQUIDS RESPONSE SHEET WAS APPROPRIATE FOR THE CORROSIVE 8.1 AND DONNED HIS SILVER SHIELD LINER AND GLOVES OVER THEM. THEN HE PROCEEDED TO TEAR OFF 5 INCHES OF PH TAPE AND TESTED FOR A RESULT OF 12-13 PH, WHICH LEAD JOSEPH TO APPLY SODIUM BICARBONATE, AFTER NEUTRALIZING IT TO A PH OF 8, HE ABSORBED THE MATERIAL AND COLLECTED THE PACKAGE COMPONENTS AND RETURNED TO THE CAGE FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. AFTER FOLLOWING THE WASTE DISPOSAL CHART AND PROCESSING THE MATERIAL, HE DECONTAMINATED HIS PPE.
THERE WAS A DECLARED HAZMAT BY THE UNLOAD. I WENT TO MY CAGE AND GRABBED THE APPROPRIATE SPILL CART AND FOLLOWED THE DECISION TREE CHART. IT TOLD ME EXACTLY HOW TO CLEAN THE SPILL

column168: FRTL unit left the roadway due to the driver experiencing a medical event and crashed into the side of a rock cliff wall.  Substantial damage was done to the right side of the tractor and right side of the cargo tank.  The rock wall ruptured the cargo tank which allowed almost all of the cargo to be spilled.  The force of the impact caused the internal bulkheads to breach which allowed the product to flow out of the holes torn into the side of the cargo tank.  The Kentucky EPA responded and dispatched Ecotech emergency response to the scene.  Extensive efforts were made to mitigate the release of product into the environment.  Remediation activities are continuing.
column169: The FRTL unit was equipped with roll stability control which prevented a rollover of the unit which minimized injury to our driver.  No other vehicles or individuals were involved in this crash.

column168: On 02/15/2018, at 18:50, personnel in the Niagara Falls yard discovered UCLX30028, a Residue tank car of Hydrochloric Acid, experiencing a vapor release from the top of the car. The car was isolated and Dow Chemical, NYS DEC and NRC were notified.  (CHEMTREC 2018021500259. The response team from Occidental Chemical Corporation was requested to the scene and found the tank car was having a vaper release due to the securement bolts on the liquid fill port being less than tool tight. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Pete Kirk 989-636-0123. Occidental Chemical corporation personnel corrected all defects and decontaminated the Rail car. Rail car was then released and allowed to be placed at industry. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1.     Cause Code:224  NARRI:17

column168: A PXC DRIVER IN THE PROCESS OF OFF LOADING 50% H2O2 SPILLED LES THAN ONE GALLON OF PRODUCT ON THE GROUND. THE STANDBY ATTENDANT IMMEDIATELY DILUTED THE AREA WITH WATER. THERE WERE NO INJURIES AND NO ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACTS. PEROXYCHEM DRIVER USED 3 SECTIONS OF 20 FT HOSE (60 FT) TO REACH THE DELIVERY TANK. AFTER DELIVERY INTO CUSTOMER TANK DRIVER HOOKED UP THE NITROGEN BOTTLE TO BLOW THE RESIDUAL H2O2 INTO CUSTOMER TANK. WHILE STORING THE HOSES INTO THE TRAILER HOSE TUBES, THE DRIVER WAS EMPTYING THE REMAINING H2O2 INTO A DRAIN BUCKET AND MISSED THE BUCKET ALLOWING H2O2 TO SPILL OVER ONTO THE SURROUNDING AREAS.
column169: THE INCIDENT INVOLVING THE PEROXYCHEM DRIVER WAS DISCUSSED WITH HIS TRAINER. THE DRIVER PERFORMED A RE-TRAINING REGARDING PUMP OFF PROCEDURES WITH LEAD TRAINER.

column168: THE 1-855-NEXEO4U CALL CENTER (ECC) RECEIVED A CALL ON 02/08/18 AT 15:10 EST FROM TIM ARMBRUSTER WITH NEXEO SOLUTIONS IN TWINS-BURG, OH REPORTING THE FOLLOWING. DENNIS SCHINKE WAS MAKING A DELIVERY TO CUSTOMER CALVARY INDUSTRIES, INC. IN FAIRFIELD, OH ON 02/08/18 AT 12:45 EST, WHEN A RELEASE OCCURRED. TWENTY GALLONS OF TRIETANOLINE 99% TECH RELEASED TO THE ASPHALT UNLOADING AREA AT THE CUSTOMER SITE DURING UNLOADING OF THE TRACTOR TANKER (#35912, #34359). SCHINKE WAS PREPARING TO UNLOAD FROM THE TANKER, CHARGED THE LINE BUT NOTHING FLOWED. THINKING THE EXTERNAL VALVE WAS CLOSED HE WENT TO THE BLEEDER VALVE TO RELIEVE PRESSURE BUT THERE WAS NO PRODUCT AT THE VALVE. SCHINKE BELIEVED THE LINE HAD NO PRESSURE AND BEGAN TO UNCLAMP THE HOSE AT THE EXTERNAL VALVE, RELEASING THE PRODUCT. SCHINKE WAS IN FULL PPE, NO PRODUCT MADE IT TO THE SKIN, EYES OR MOUTH. SCHINKE WASHED AND CHANGED CLOTHES. DRIVER HAD STATED NO MEDICAL ATTENTION REQUIRED, ECC TRANSFERRED SCHINKE TO MEDCOR. THE CUSTOMER SITE CLEANED THE SPILL AND IS NOT REQUESTING ASSISTANCE. ECC NOTIFIED CHRISTOPHER BYERMAN.

column169: Accident was the result of deteriorating weather and road conditions and the driver's inability to proceed to an area where the road was being maintained. column168: USPS PRIORITY MAIL TRACKING NUMBER 9405511699000523197570 ARRIVED TO OUR OFFICE AT 1324 ON 1 FEB 2018 TO BE FORWARDED TO OUR CLIENT VIA A PASSENGER AIRCRAFT IN THE BERRY ISLANDS, BAHAMAS. A HAZMAT TRAINED LOGISTICS EMPLOYEE HEARD WHAT HE BELIEVED TO BE AEROSOL CANS IN THE BOX AND PROCEEDED TO OPEN THE BOX TO PERFORM AN INSPECTION ON THE CONTENTS PRIOR TO INTERNATIONAL SHIPMENT AND DISCOVERED SIX 16 OUNCE CANS OF SEA FOAM MOTOR TREATMENT. THE CANS ARE MARKED “FLAMMABLE”. AFTER PROCURING THE SDS FROM THE MANUFACTURER, WE SAW IT CLEARLY STATES IT IS UN1993 OR AT VERY LEAST ORM-D. THE PACKAGING WAS SIMPLY A US POSTAL SERVICE FLAT RATE PRIORITY MAIL SHIPPING BOX.  THERE WAS NO INNER PROTECTION AS REQUIRED BY THE US POST OFFICE. THE OUTER BOX DID NOT HAVE ANY DOT OR IATA LABLEING DESIGNATING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WERE IN THE SHIPMENT. THERE WAS ALSO SIX CANS IN THE PACKAGE AND POSTAL REGULATIONS ONLY ALLOW FOR TWO IN ONE PACKAGE. INSPECTION OF THE PACKAGING SHOWS DAMAGE TO THE CARDBOARD AND SUBSEQUENT DAMAGE TO THREE OF THE METAL CANS (CIRCLE IN RED). THE PACKAGE WAS SHIPPED BY ICE AUTO PARTS IN PHILADELPHIA, PA FOR A FINAL DESTINATION IN GREAT IN GREAT HARBOUR CAY, BERRY ISLANDS, BAHAMAS. TROPIC OCEAN AIRWAYS IS A WILL NOT CARRY SHIPPER AND THEREFORE REJECTS THIS SHIPMENT. THE SHIPMENT WILL BE HELD IN AN APPROPRIATE FLAMMABLES LOCKER UNTIL SUCH TIME AS THIS INVESTIGATION ALLOWS FOR DISPOSAL. NO PRODUCT WAS RELEASED DURING SHIPMENT AND ALL CONTAINERS ARE INTACT, ALTHOUGH THREE ARE DENIED.
column169: TROPIC OCEAN AIRWAYS’ LOGISTICS MANAGER REACHED OUT TO THE SHIPPER TO NOTIFY THEM OF THE ISSUE IN AN ATTEMPT TO PREVENT FURTHER OCCURRENCES. IN SPEAKING TO ICE AUTO PARTS, THEY WERE EXTREMELY CONCERNED, HOWEVER THEY DID NOT SEEM TO BE VERY EDUCATED ON SHIPPING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS/DANGEROUS GOODS. IT WOULD SEEM THEIR TRAINING PROGRAM SHOULD BE EVALUATED TO ENSURE THEIR EMPLOYEES KNOW PROPER SHIPPING STANDARDS. THEY WERE APOLOGETIC AND SEEMED WILLING TO COOPERATE.

column168: A material handler was moving the drum by hand. When setting the drum back flat on the floor, he failed to notice a rock under the drum. Upon setting the drum flat, the rock punctured the bottom head spilling approximately one half gallon of material onto the warehouse floor. The drum was immediately over packed and the material was cleaned up and the debris properly disposed of. The over packed material was shipped to its final destination without further incident.
column169: The need for better situational awareness and housekeeping procedures were reviewed and implemented.

column168: On February 20, 2018 at 1451 hours, personnel at CSXT Avon Yard discovered GATX 54038, a residue UN3289, Toxic Liquid, Corrosive, Inorganic, N.O.S. (Sodium Sulfide Solution), Class 6.1, (8), PGII tank car to have released product from the bottom outlet valve area. The car was isolated and the Shipper, Heritage-Crystal Clean LLC. was notified via CHEMTREC, report 2018022000195. A CSX Emergency Response contractor, Sunpro, was dispatched to the scene. Upon inspection it was determined the bottom outlet valve flange had 4 of 4 bolts less than tool tight. As a preventative measure each of the bolts were tightened tool tight to stop the leak. After further investigation it was discovered that Heritage-Crystal Clean was moving the car with an OTMA-3 to a home shop for repairs.  A HAZMATHOLD was placed on the car until Heritage-Crystal Clean can clean & purge the car.

column168: DRIVER HAD PARKED FOR HIS 10 HOUR BREAK. HE WAS CONDUCTING HIS POST-TRIP INSPECTION WHEN HE NOTICED A DRIP COMING FROM THE EXTERNAL VALVE AREA. HE IMMEDIATELY PLACED A BUCKET UNDER THE DRIP AND CALLED CENTRAL DISPATCH. HAZMAT CLEAN-UP CREW (OMI ENVIRONMENTAL SOLUTIONS) WAS CONTACTED TO RESPOND TO THE SCENE. NUT FOR PACKING WAS WHERE THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM. NUT WAS TIGHTENED TO STOP THE DRIP. OMI ENVIRONMENTAL SOLUTIONS CONDUCTED THE REPAIR AND CLEAN-UP SUCCESSFULLY. CAUSATION OF THE PACKING FAILURE IS CURRENTLY UNDER THE INVESTIGATION. LOOSE NUT IS THE CAUSATION TO THE LEAK ON THE EXTERNAL VALVE. INTERNAL PACKING ON INTERNAL VALVE WAS ALSO LEAKING, WHICH IS WHAT CAUSED PRODUCT TO GET THE EXTERNAL VALVE. CAUSATION TO THIS LEAK WAS AGING PACKING.

column168: At 0600 hrs. on 2/27/2018, while the WLE Brewster Yard Car inspector was inspecting an inbound train, he noticed an odor coming from SHQX 5797.  He notified the Brewster Yard Master who then contacted myself, John Vergis Environmental Officer for the WLE.  I came out to inspect the car and when I got on top the car, I noticed that the safety pin for the protective housing lid was not installed but hanging by its chain.  I also noticed that the seal, number 36518 was in place but had been cut.  I opened the housing Lid and noticed that the rubber cover that is to cover the pressure relief device was taken off and laying to the side.  I reinstalled the cover on the PRD.  I checked all the valves to see what was leaking and noticed that the vapor valve was leaking through the valve plug.  I tried the valve handle to see if it was loose and it was.  I tightened the valve handle and the leak stopped.  I looked to see if the valve plug was loose but it was not, it was tool tight but the thread sealant was not sufficient to prevent a leak.  I took the valve plug out and reinstalled thread sealant and then reinstalled the valve plug.  I installed a new seal on the housing lid, seal number 971787.  I then released the car for service.    NARRI: 2(4+5) x 2=36                 Cause Code: 379

column168: While traveling south on I-41 near Vinland, WI another motorist notified our driver he was leaking material from his trailer. The driver stopped at Exit 124 and parked on a nose down slope to attempt to keep the released material in the trailer. Local law enforcement was summoned and instructed our driver to proceed to a Park & Ride adjacent to Exit 124 to conduct the remediation in a safer area. An in-house emergency response team responded. The trailer was deemed a confined space and after donning appropriate PPE and SCBA, the response team entered the trailer, identified and removed the leaking container. The leaking container was over packed along with the cleanup debris and transported to its original destination without further incident.

column168: Waste was properly loaded and secured in transport vehicle and on its way to the designated facility. The unit was rear-ended at a significant speed, as a result of weather-related road conditions. While the driver was successful in keeping the transport vehicle on the roadway, upon inspection by the local fire department, a damaged IBC was identified. Due to impact, the damage resulted in a release of its contents. The temperature at the time of inspection was well below freezing, causing the contents of the damaged container to freeze immediately. The release was contained to the trailer; no soil, waterways or storm drains were impacted. A response team was dispatched to remediate the trailer and repackage the contents of the damaged container. In proper personal protective equipment, the response team was successful in remediating the trailer and inspecting the integrity of the remaining containers. A state notification was made and Report # 2018-0101 was generated.
column169: An internal investigation was launched and a claim to the responsible party’s insurance company was filed.

column168: JANUARY 23: SHIPPER CONTACTED FED-EX TRADE NETWORKS TO MOVE A SHIPMENT FROM LOUISVILLE, KY TO HAGALIL, ISRAEL. THE SHIPMENT ARRIVED IN OUR CHICAGO AREA WAREHOUSE IN A NON-SPECIFICATION FIBERBOARD BOX, WITH NO HAZARDOUS MARKINGS ON THE OUTSIDE. THE PACKAGE WAS LOADED AS PART OF A CONSOLIDATION, BOUND FOR JFK AIRPORT, IN NEW YORK TO BE LOADED ON AN AIRPLANE TO FINAL DESTINATION. FEBRUARY 6: EL AL CARGO, THE AIRLINE OPENED THE PACKAGE TO INSPECT AND DISCOVERED ANOTHER NON-SPECIFICATION FIBERBOARD BOX BEARING THE HAZARD CLASS 9 LABEL, AND A MARKING WITH UN3268 SAFETY DEVICES. FEBRUARY 26: FED-EX TRADE NETWORKS ADVISED CUSTOMER TO HAVE THE PACKAGE SENT TO A 3RD PARTY DG PACKER AND HAVE THEM CREATE THE SHIPPER’S DECLARATION OF DANGEROUS GOODS. CUSTOMER HAS DECIDED TO UTILIZE ANOTHER FREIGHT FORWARDER AS FED-EX TRADE NETWORKS REFUSES TO MOVE THIS SHIPMENT UNTIL IT IS PROPERLY DECLARED AND PACKAGED.

While on an interstate highway, the driver noticed his tank trailer had developed a leak. The driver immediately pulled over and saw that the tank gauge device had broken, and had developed a leak. The quick thinking driver immediately placed the tanker under vacuum, which ended the release. The driver then used packing material, threaded rod and a nut to effect a stable repair. The highway police did stop and assess the situation and found that since the actual release was a small amount, the day very windy, and the acetone quick to evaporate, there was nothing on the road way or vehicle to clean up. The tank continued to the nearby intended destination without further incident. After the tank was unloaded, it was sent for a permanent repair and retesting.     Later investigation revealed that the tank gauge mechanism had recently been replaced, and that design of the replacement was prone to loosening and coming undone.     This release was reported to the state: NJ DEP 11:27EST 18-02-05-1128-20 Operator #69.
column169: At the time this tanker was placed into transportation, there was no evidence of a leak or mechanical issue. Our asset maintenance department has contacted the vendor who installed the tank gauging device that failed, and asked the vendor to alert the manufacturer of the issue encountered with this device in this application. A new tank gauge using a different configuration was used to repair this tanker.

column168: On February 2, 2018, at approximately 10 am CST; Sully Transport driver, Jeff Mercer, was in route to Glidden, IA Casey’s Convenience Store. Jeff was traveling westbound on US highway 30. Speed limit 55 mph. Jeff was approximately 2 miles west of Grand Junction, IA in Greene County at the crossroad intersection of US 30 and Green County Rd P33/S. Ave.    The weather was cloudy with a very light snow falling. Jeff, looking at the intersection seeing a white pickup Eastbound coming towards him. As Jeff pass the intersection (S. Ave.) he suddenly feels an impact /jolt to his truck, as he looks in the driver’s side mirror, he sees a fireball and he sees his trailer on the highway skidding behind and to his left in the Eastbound lane. Somewhat shocked he steers to the right shoulder/north side of highway 30. As he is doing this, the trailer goes past him. Jeff jumps out of his truck cab and is fearful the pickup coming towards him gets stopped and calls 911. Jeff runs towards his burning trailer. – The pickup following Jeff westbound for an unknown reason.    The pickup following Jeff for unknown reason ended up in the ditch behind our trailer. Jeff saw that the right front wheel had extensive damage. We can only assume it hit debris on the highway from the other truck. There was a front axle, engine, and transmission on the highway that came from the other truck.    One of the first on the scene was another one of Sully’s owner-operators, John Schneider. John was behind the eastbound pickup by about a half minute. As John came upon the accident, not knowing what just happened and sees a truck on the westbound shoulder/north side of the highway and did not recognize what was burning in the ditch on the south side of the highway. As John got close and saw the Sully logo on the tank and then looked ahead and saw the 4” orange gasoline drop hose lying in the middle of the highway, then he knew it was a gasoline tanker. At 9:58 am John called Brent and asked if I was aware of this and I said no & John said it looked like our truck was “T-boned” by a livestock truck.     John was unaware the Sully drivers (Jeff Mercer’s) truck tractor was the truck on the westbound side of the highway at this point the fire was big enough John could not tell if the truck tractor was or was not hooked to the trailer.  Brent asked John to park his truck a safe distance and find out what exactly had happened and to call him back in 5 minutes.     Brent found out from dispatch who the driver was and what exactly he had loaded. He had loaded 8300 gals of gasohol (gasoline with ethanol).  In the meantime, John found our driver, Jeff Mercer, safe. He took a few photos and sent them to dispatch so as to not tie up my phone. He did not have anything else to report except that the driver of the pickup was in the fire but that the driver was now safe. The driver of the livestock truck had been ejected from his truck cab and was alive and that was all he knew. By this time responders
column169: I do not think there is anything that Sully Transport can do to prevent an accident such as this one. One can not predict or control the actions of another driver.

column168: On February 11, 2018, at approximately 09:00, DANA Transport arrived at Brenntag Northeast, LLC, 81 W Huller Lane, Reading, PA, to deliver trailer #8424, containing a shipment of heptane from Exxon Mobile Chemical Company, Channahon, IL. which Brenntag had ordered.  Upon his arrival, on Sunday morning, the driver checked in with Security, and as Brenntag Northeast was not operating at the time, was directed to drop the trailer in a specified area, for future unloading by Brenntag personnel.  On the morning of February 12, 2018, during routine operations, at approximately 07:10, a Brenntag Northeast contractor discovered that the trailer was leaking. He immediately reported this to Brenntag Northeast personnel. Brenntag Northeast personnel identified the leak as being at the rear of the trailer and laid absorbents throughout the areas impacted by the spill and diked the storm drains. Senior Management was notified.  The product was off loaded from the leaking trailer into another empty trailer Brenntag had on-site. CURA, Brenntag’s on call response and remediation contractor was called to perform the clean-up. PADEP was notified. DANA Transport, the carrier involved, was notified of the situation.  After unloading of the leaking trailer, Brenntag was able to assess the cause of the leak. The eight bolts connecting the outlet valve to the flange of the trailer were only hand tight, which allowed the material to leak from the flange.  Brenntag is unable to estimate the length of the release, as the weather from the time it was delivered until just before discovery was raining and foggy. During the cleanup weather was clear.  CURA sent a response and remediation contractor to the site, which cleaned up the absorbents, and assessed if any remediation was necessary. Remediation of the asphalt area where the material had leaked was required and completed the next day.
column169: Brenntag Northeast personnel met February 12, 2018, to assess the incident and see if there was anything we could do to prevent or minimize this type of incident in the future.  It was decided that going forward, any transports entering the site will be scrutinized more closely by the Security team to assess if anything is leaking at the time of arrival.

column168: THE KA BULK TRANSPORT, LLC (KA BULK) WAS TRAVELING NORTHBOUND ON HIGHWAY 41 NEAR CHASSELL, MICHIGAN. THE DRIVER OF CLAIMANT VEHICLE #2 WAS KILLED. AFTER IMPACT, THE KA BULK UNIT WENT OFF ONTO THE SHOULDER OF THE NORTHBOUND LANE. THE TANK TRAILER DISCONNECTED FROM THE TRACTOR AND ROLLED OVER. THE TANK SHELL WAS COMPROMISED AND APPROXIMATELY 4006 GALLONS OF GASOLINE AND 1539 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL WERE RELEASED. THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED ON A BRIDGE OVER THE STURGEON RIVER AND SOME OF THE SPILLED GASOLINE/DIESEL FUEL WAS ABLE TO IMPACT THE RIVER. REMEDIATION REMAINS ONGOING.

column168: FLIGHT INFORMATION PASSENGER: CRAIG TRUEMPI FLIGHT: DL 4671 MSP-ATW   PASSENGER CRAIG TRUEMPI WAS TRAVELING FROM MINNEAPOLIS ST PAUL (MSP) TO APPLETON (ATW) ON FLIGHT DL 4671. AFTER THE FLIGHT HAD LANDED IN ATW, SMOKE WAS SEEN COMING FROM THE FIRST CLASS COAT CLOSET. THE FLIGHT ATTENDANT THEN INFORMED THE CAPTAIN OF THE SMOKE. THE CAPTAIN THEN CALLED THE TOWER FOR THE FIRE DEPARTMENT. BOTH FLIGHT ATTENDANTS OPENED THE COAT CLOSET TO FIND THAT REASON FOR THE SMOKE WAS COMING FROM A CARRY-ON BAG THAT WAS PLACED IN THE CLOSET. THE AIRCRAFT WAS JUST SHORT OF THE GATE AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD ARRIVED SO THE CAPTAIN DECIDED TO DO AN EXPEDITED DEPLANING. ALL THE PASSENGERS AND CREW USED THE MAIN CABIN DOOR TO EXIT THE AIRCRAFT. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT BOARDED THE AIRCRAFT AND FOUND THAT THE BAG IN THE COAT CLOSET. THE BAG CONTAINED TWO 12-VOLT BATTERIES (NON-LITHIUM) HAD BEEN PLACED IN THE BAG AND HAD MADE CONTACT WITH WIRES AND METAL THAT WAS ALSO IN THE BAG. THE BATTERY AND BAG WAS THEN GIVEN BACK TO THE PASSENGER BY THE FIRE DEPARTMENT.   I DO NOT KNOW THE MAKE MODEL OF THE BATTERY, ONLY THAT IT WAS A 12-VOLT (NON-LITHIUM). I BELIEVE IT WAS AN ALKALINE BATTERY AND IS NOT REGULATED.  ONE OF THE FLIGHT ATTENDANTS WAS TREATED FOR SMOKE INHALATION FOR THE NEXT DAY.

Contractor reports a tote was placed below the leak as containment (tote contains just over 50 gallons). Approximately 30-50 gallons reached the ground and mixed with puddles of water. column168: On February 24, 2018 at 1158 ET, Chad Jacobs with Trimac US contacted ERTS regarding a UN1265 "N-Pentane" release at the Dedicated Tank Cleaning Services; 2700 175th St, Lansing, IL 60438. It was reported that a Trimac tractor tanker (470409) was found with a leak coming from the piping near the belly valve. Approximately 1 gallon dripped to the soft gravel below. No drains or waterways were impacted by the release and the release has been secured by on site personnel. 1215 ERTS coordinated with a network contractor, Hazchem, who provided a 2 hour ETA. A DOT5800 is required due to the PGI and container size. No further reporting shall be conducted at this time.    1519 ET: Contractor has finished their assessment of the tanker. It was possible that a pipe leading to the leaking valve may have contained residual product resulting in the release. The pipe ran a significant portion of the tanker. The contractor emptied approximately 20 gallons of material into a drum from the pipe at the back end. Once the pipe was emptied, the leak initially stopped. Shortly after, the valve began to leak again. The contractor suspects that the internal safety valve is malfunctioned/damaged. Contractor reports that the tanker is not fit to be moved. ERTS will coordinate with Chad Jacobs with Trimac to determine the next course of action.     1540 ET: ERTS has coordinated with the contractor and spoken with Chad Jacobs. The contractor will return Monday morning (Exact time to be determined) to conduct a tanker transfer. The contractor will secure the valve the best the can with puddy and absorbent pads. A containment area will be created around the valve in the event the securement fails. The valve is slow leaking and is not anticipated to leak outside the valve and containment area. There are two tankers onsite that can be used as transfer tankers. All parties involved understand the plan.     The impacted gravel/soil around the leaking valve has been hand dug. The area around the valve has been wiped down.    Waste Count:  (1) 55 gallon metal drum containing 20 liquid gallons of product.  (1) 55 gallon metal drum containing impacted absorbents/soil/gravel.    All waste has been staged on site as the drums will be still used for Monday's transfer. Chad Jacobs and the driver have approved of the drums being staged onsite.

column168: At approximately 3:58 pm on Wednesday 02/07/18 a liquid spill was reported inside a trailer.  The spill was originating from damage to the bottom of a 330 gallon tote.  Weight of this tote full was indicated to be 3376 lbs prior to the spill, gallons not determined but estimated at close to full and less than 330.  The spilled material was a waste material (DOT Shipping Name: UN2924, Waste Flammable Liquids, Corrosive, n.o.s. (Isopropanol, Formic Acid), 3 (8), PGIII, RQ(D002)[Used Weighted Formic Acid and Wash Water].  This material spilled onto the floor of the trailer and then out of the side of the trailer onto the ground.  The tote was being unloaded from a trailer by forklift, Root Cause indicates Forklift Operator error resulted in tote puncture and spill of material.    Multiple lines of boom and absorbent  placed to halt the spread of spilled material, sandbags placed in nearby ditch to prevent material spread if the event of boom and absorbent breach occurred.  Notification was made to Louisiana State Police, LSP Incident# 18-00680 was issued.  Local Fire and Hazmat Teams came onsite to ensure the situation was contained.  LDEQ came onsite to ensure that the spill was contained and appropriately remediated.  Emergency Spill response company USES arrived onsite at approx 6:30 pm to begin assessing and delineating spill affected area, recover, and decontaminate affected areas.

column168: While performing a routine inspection, the driver saw HazMat releasing from an internal valve mounting bolt. No obvious damage to the bolt or valve was seen, nor any holes or cracks. The last routine inspection stop was about 2 hours earlier, so we estimate the release duration at somewhere between 4 and 6 hours.  The carrier sent the CTMV to a repair shop and the mechanic reported that the internal valve mounting gasket was cracked.        Event #67960.

column168: At approximately 1530 this afternoon February 18, 2018 yardmaster Mooney notified me that the Manchester carman had found a leaking tank car. The car UTLX 23471 was located in track 13-8 about 4 car lengths north of the Central Bridge. Upon arriving I found the car leaking on both sides with material cascading from the covered dome. Kirk notified ITC of the leak and had M&M responding to the leak. They arrived at approximately 1830 and secured several loose bolts under the dome covering the fill line and the dip tube. This all was completed at approximately 1900 and PT241 has resumed switching. The car has been bad ordered with the clerk and will be placed in track 13-26 for observation and cleaning. No injuries resulted from the leak.     M&M report:  On February 18, 2018, at approximately 15:30 hours, Kirk Higbie, Director of Environmental & Safety for the Port Terminal Railroad Association contacted M&M Protection and advised that there was a leaking methonol rail tank car in the Manchester Yard, 8934 Manchester Houston, Texas 77012, Track # 8.  • Personnel responded with materials and equipment to remediate.  • Yard Master was on site at all times and tracks were locked out.  • Railcar UTLX23471 appereared to be leaking from the valves protective housing.  • Personnel climbed to the top of railcar, cut the seal #ITC0049390 from dome, opened it and found  o All four (4) bolts on blind flange were hand tight,  o All eight (8) bolts on the air valve were hand tight.  o All four (4) bolts of the vacuum releif valve were hand tight.  • The railcar had alrerady vented any excess pressure and the liquid that escaped had evaporated due to temperture.  • The bolts were tightened and a new seal was placed on the dome.  • Crew then demobilized and returned to service.
column169: Intercontinental Terminals Corp (ITC) personnel were notified of the incident and are investigating the root cause in order to prevent future occurrence.

To mitigate a further release, the CTMV remained parked until the valve was repaired.      Event #67946.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE TRAVELING, HIGGINS TRANSPORT WAS INVOLVED IN A VEHICLE ACCIDENT, CAUSING TRUCK TO ROLLOVER OFF ROAD SHOULDER, RESULTING IN THE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 5,855 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL. FREE PRODUCT RELEASED TO A DRY DRAINAGE SWALE AND SOIL ADJACENT THE HIGHWAY. THERE WERE NO STATE WATERS AFFECTED OR THREATENED BY THE RELEASE. WAYNE’S TOWING RESPONDED TO RECOVER THE VEHICLE, AND ASSIST IN RESPONSE. SCIM, SUBSIDIARY OF WAYNE’S, PERFORMED THE CLEANUP. SCIM CONTINUED EXCAVATION ACTIVITY UNTIL ALL CONTAMINATION WAS RECOVERED. SCDHEC OVERSAW RESPONSE ACTIONS AND WAS SATISFIED WITH SCIM EFFORTS. DISPOSAL WAS COORDINATED IN ACCORDANCE WITH LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.
column169: HIGGINS TRANSPORT WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND REINFORCE SAFE HANDLING PROCEDURES AND DRIVER SAFETY TO ALL PERSONNEL.

column168: On Feb 11th, 2018 at 11:00 AM an Air Products driver picked up the loaded hydrogen tube trailer from the Air Products Wilmington, CA plant. In the process of making a delivery, the driver was stopped at a traffic light in Diamond Bar, CA at approximately 1:15 PM when he heard a loud bang and observed flames emitting from the trailer behind him. The driver immediately exited the tractor, signaled people in the immediate vicinity to move to a safe location, and called 9-1-1 from a nearby parking lot. Emergency services and Air Products personnel worked to put out the fire, isolate the leaking tubes, and depressurize the tubes to allow for transportation of the trailer to an Air Products facility. At approximately 3:00 AM on Feb 12th, the venting of the trailer tubes was completed, emergency responders left scene, and a tow truck was dispatched to move the trailer to the Air Products Santa Fe Springs Terminal.  Upon visual inspection of the failed trailer, damage was observed on multiple tubes and it was identified that seven (7) pressure relief device (PRD) assemblies on the back of the trailer were ejected from their corresponding tubes. The subsequent investigation identified the following preliminary root causes for the failure: (1) one of the PRDs [ejected from tube #14] was found to have the incorrect pressure rating, 5,833 psi vs the correct 10,000 psi [with a trailer operating pressure of 7,500 psi], (2) compression fittings on the PRD discharge vent piping were assembled incompletely.   The incident investigation is currently ongoing to finalize the root causes and corrective actions.
column169: As an immediate action, Air Products performed a 100% inspection of all vehicles constructed with the same specification cylinder to identify/replace any incorrectly rated PRDs and repair any incorrectly assembled compression fittings.  In addition, the following items have been put in place to ensure PRDs and fittings are correctly installed following requalification.     Air Products implemented 100% quality inspection of its vendors' work with particular focus on PRD set point and vent tube assembly.     Detailed work instructions were developed in conjunction with the third party requalification facility to ensure trailers have correctly rated PRDs and correctly installed vent piping following a requalification.

column168: While loading, the driver noticed jet fuel running out from above the 5th wheel. The driver shut down loading. The terminal personnel began draining product from the tank. An estimated 65 gallons has spilled out of the tank before the tank could be emptied. An investigation reveled that the tube that routes air and electrical lines through the tank had filled with water and frozen. The freezing cracked the tube and allowed the product to leak out.
column169: All company tank trailers are being inspected and resealed at the top of the trailer to prevent a reoccurrence.

column168: On 2/20/18 at approximately 4:30 pm two IMTT Operations Supervisors noticed 2 oil on the ground just past the pump they were driving by. They pulled over and walked the 30" A-line in the area and did not see any leaks where the oil was coming from at the time.  One of the supervisors contacted US Ecology (IMTT's OSRO)who dispatched a vacuum truck to remove approximately 25 gallons of oil and water mixture. After removing the water and oil mixture it became apparent that the leak had not stopped.  At this point the decision was made to evacuate the remaining product in the line and start excavating under the line to determine the source of the leak.  The initial excavation had to stop due to the fact the line was run under an adjacent roadway within the terminal.  The roadway was blocked off and additional equipment brought in to extract the pipeline.  Upon inspection it was determined that exterior corrosion on the line caused the leak.
column169: IMTT conducted a Root Cause Analysis and determined that several factors lead to the pin-hole sized leak in the line.  These included: 1.) The pipe was inside a sleeve and run under the roadway.  2.) The pipe was installed pre-1970's and was not coated and had no cathodic protection.  3.) The pipe was subjected to vibration during use over a long time period.  Preventative measures include: Running the new section of pipe above ground on supports and grout and cap the old sleeve; Prime and paint the new section of pipe; Install marine boards on the new supports to prevent metal to metal contact.  The re-installation of the pipe will meet all PHMSA requirements.

column168: WHILE OPERATING IN ON I-90 EASTBOUND AS DRIVER CRESTED A HILL HE ENCOUNTERED A REDUCED SPEED VEHICLE IN LANE DUE TO PLOWING ACTIVITY CAUSING SNOW CLOUD. AS DRIVER CHANGED LANES THE SECOND TRAILER MADE CONTACT WITH SLOWER MOVING VEHICLE AND IMPACT CAUSED CTMV TO LEAVE ROADWAY AND OVERTURN ONTO ITS SIDE. IMPACT CAUSED PRODUCT LEAK FROM MANHOLE COVER. DRIVER UNABLE TO RE-SECURE DOME COVER TO STOP LEAK. RESPONSE AUTHORITIES DECIDED TO ALLOW PRODUCT TO CONTINUE TO EXIT CTMV UNTIL LEAK STOPPED 3 HOURS LATER. INTERNAL INVESTIGATION INDICATED DOME COVER WAS PROPERLY SECURED AS REQUIRED. DEGREE OF RELEASE IS DIRECT RESULT OF ON-SITE AUTHORITIES REFUSAL TO ALLOW ACTIONS TO END LEAK EARLIER. INITIAL CAUSE OF ACCIDENT IS DRIVER ERROR.
column169: DRIVER AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL RECEIVE REMEDIAL TRAINING IN PROPER INSPECTION AND VERIFICATION OF SECUREMENT DEVICES ON DOME COVERS AND OTHER LOADING AND UNLOADING DEVICES BEFORE PLACING UNIT ON PUBLIC ROADWAYS. DRIVER WILL ALSO RECEIVE REMEDIAL TRAINING IN DEFENSIVE DRIVER AND SPEED TO WEATHER/ROADWAY CONDITIONS.

column168: The employee was at his first stop for the day. he prepared the bobtail for delivery and went to activate the PTO to run the pump he heard and saw a release of propane from underneath the bobtail. He immediately hit the ESO on t eh remote shutting the bobtail down.After activating the ESV he check to see if the leak stopped. when it did not he called his district manager for further instructions. The district manager then called Industrial Propane Service to fix the leak. when they arrived they were able to get leak stopped. It is estimated that no more than 25 gallons of liquid was lost. The remaining propane was pumped off into storage using a compressor. The head of a bolt broke off on a flange between the high-pressure side of the pump and supply piping to the meter causing that seal between to leak. That was the main cause of the leak for the release. The truck has been taken out of service. No injuries, no property damage.
column169: The employee is a new employee that was the last one to do a meter creep on this bobtail. We had him explain the process for performing a meter creep and was satisfied that he completed the task correctly the last time it was performed on this unit. To help the employee out we will have an experienced employee help him with the next few meter creeps he performs to help coach him.

column168: Tank car NATX 252588 was reported with residue product on the sides of the tank car around the manway nozzle.  The BNSF Responder reported NATX 252588 three manway lid swing bolts were less than tool tight allowing product to release when the car was moved.  BNSF Responder inspected the manway and properly tool tightened the manway lid swing bolts, which ended any further release of product.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Car was noted as having a drip from the four-bolt flange that bolts the bottom outlet valve nozzle to the bottom of the tank car. Three of the four bolts were noted as loose and one was missing/broken. BNSF HazMat Responder arrived on scene and proceeded to tighten the three existing bolts. That action did stop the further release of product. Approximately 5-gallons were releases onto the ground, into snow.
column169: Shipper needs to ensure the proper securement of the bolts on the tank car prior to transportation.

column25: Energy Logistics for Coleman Oil Company
column168: The tank car was noted in the yard as leaking a substantial amount of product from the four-bolt flange that secures the bottom outlet valve nozzle to the bottom of the tank car. Upon inspection by a BNSF HazMat Responder, it was determined that the four securement bolts were loose. Upon attempting to tighten the bolts, only one could be tightened and the remaining three were stripped and unable to be tightened. A contractor then applied a large ratchet strap completely around the tank car and under the BOV. Pressure was applied and the leak subsided. The car was then moved over containment for the remainder of the night.      The following day, transfer of the product from the defective car to an empty car commenced and was successful in transferring the remaining product.
column169: The shipper must ensure that all securement bolts are properly tightened prior to transportation.

column168: Tank car BNSF 880427 was reported releasing product in the railyard from the top operated bottom outlet valve.  The BNSF Responder reported leak source was at BNSF 880427's top operated bottom outlet valve flange.  The BNSF Responder determined that the top operated bottom outlet valve gasket was not properly sealing at the bottom outlet causing residue product to release.  BNSF Responder contained the release until no further product was remaining in the railcar.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: While offloading one of the 274 gallon plastic totes from an Advance Container Trailer (ACT) our staff didn't realize a small section of the e-track had pulled away.  As the tote was being removed this small section of metal made a tear in the container resulting in a spill of product.  Approximately 15 gallons went to the trailer floor and was immediately clean out with absorb-all.  The material was transferred to a compliant tote and prepared for transport.  Spill debris was disposed of in drums and prepared for transport.
column169: The incident was reviewed with the trailer owner (ACT) to ensure the integrity of their trailer prior to shipment to Clean Harbors.  Also and immediate safety meeting was conducted with the Clean Harbors crew after the incident to review how the incident can be prevented.  The forklift driver was removed from the operating the forklift and underwent retraining on safety operations.

column168: On 2/20/18 at approximately 12:00 pm two IMTT Chemical Operators were rear loading a Langer trailer with Methylene Chloride.  During the loading the two Operators started to notice a drip coming from the flange of the trailer. When they investigated it was determined that the trailer was a side loader and only had a rear offloading tube.  They were able to blow the line back to the trailer and complete the loading process without further incident.
column169: IMTT has informed the customer of this product that we will not except side loaders with a tube.  The trailer must be a rear loader, which means the internal valve must be in the rear of the trailer to be acceptable to load.

column168: Driver was unloading and needed to move the truck, He failed to disconnect the hose and stop the flow of fuel before he did so resulting in a hose rupture & a spill of 200-300 gallons. While pulling up he stretched the hose and it ripped it apart and the fuel continued to flow while the driver tried to exit the truck and stop fuel spill. The driver is being terminated for false information. The local fire department arrived on scene and spread sand. Action Environmental was contacted to manage the spill cleanup.     Gasoline spilled onto the concrete driveway surface and appears to have flowed into an onsite drainage system. The drainage system was later determined to be part of a designed storm water management system that collects all storm water from the site and passes it through an oil/water separator before being discharged offsite. FCE eventually found the opening to the oil/water separator and determined that the gasoline was contained in the separator. Based on Action’s request, FCE determined that no gasoline had impacted any soil. Further, there was no impact to any water way.
column169: Eagle Transport Corporation discharged this driver for not following company policy. All drivers were reminded of the importance of following policies and the consequences if they do not.

column168: THE DRIVER OF THE BULK TRANSPORT UNIT WHICH WAS CARRYING 10,800 GALLONS OF ETHANOL UN1987 WAS TRAVELING ON ROUTE 481 INTERSTATE AT APPROXIMATELY 65MPH. ANOTHER VEHICLE WAS FLAGGING OUR DRIVER TO MOVE OVER AS IF SOMETHING WAS WRONG. THIS VEHICLE WAS A PICKUP TRUCK TRAVELING SOUTHBOUND IN THE PASSING LANE. OUR DRIVER MOVED OVER TO THE SHOULDER, BUT MOVED TO FAR INTO THE SOFT SHOULDER. THAT TRUCK WAS MOVING AT 4.4MPH AT THE TIME OF ROLLOVER. ENTIRE UNTI ROLLED OVER.  THE DRIVER CALLED IN TO REPORT AT 11:55AM WE DISPATCHED OVER SOIL RESPONSE TEAM, TWO OTHER TANKERS TO RESPOND, ALL ARRIVED AT 12:20-12:40PM. THE LOCAL SHERIFFS HAD SHUT DOWN THE SOUTHBOUND LANES, THE NORTHBOUND OPERATED AS NORMAL. OUR SPILL RESPONSE TEAM WORKED WITH THE NY DOT, NY DEC AND THE COAL FIRE DEPT AND SHERRIFS DEPT FOR A PLAN TO DRILL, PUMP AND CORRECT THE TRUCK ACCIDENT. WE INFORMED THE CONCERNED PARTIES OF OUR PLANS TO DRILL THE TRAILER AND PUMP/TRANSFER THE PRODUCT. THE TOWING COMPANY UPRIGHTED THE TRUCK. THE ONLY CLEANUP REQUIRED WAS 3 GALLONS OF MOTOR OIL. THE NY DEC AND NY DOT WERE SATISFIED WITH THE RESPONSE. THE HIGHWAY WAS CLOSED FROM 11:55AM UNTIL 17:38PM. ROAD CLOSURE WAS 5.5 HOURS. TRUCK WAS TOWED TO SHOP.
column169: THE BULK TRAILER FAILED INTERNALLY WITH ALL COMPONENTS AND BULK HEADS COLLAPSING INTERNALS. THE OUTER SHELL REMAINED INTACT WITH NO PUNCHER. ALL EQUIPMENT OPERATED AS DESIGNED. WE TRAIN THE DRIVERS AT QUARTERLY SAFETY MEETINGS ABOUT BEING AWARE OF THEIR SURROUNDINGS, SITE SECURITY ALONG WITH HIGHWAY SAFETY/SECURITY. THE DRIVER IN THIS CASE WAS ATTEMPTING TO GET THE VEHICLE TO FAR OFF THE HIGHWAY CONCERNED WITH BLOCKING TRAFFIC. WE HAVE SHARED THE FINDINGS WITH THE NY DOT, NY DEC AND THE COMPANY AGAIN THE PACKAGE/BULK TANK HAD NO PUNCHER TO THE OUTER SHELL AND THERE WAS NO RELEASE OTHER THAN TRUCK ENGINE OIL.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails); Forklift Accident
column168: DRIVER SELECTED FOR ROADSIDE INSPECTION. DURING THE INSPECTION, A RELEASE WAS DISCOVERED BY THE AUTHORITIES. THE MARYLAND DEQ DETERMINED THAT THE RELEASE WAS CONTAINED AND ESCORTED THE DRIVER BACK TO THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION IN BALTIMORE WHERE THE LOAD WAS PICKED UP.    UPON THE TRAILER'S ARRIVAL (1330HRS) THE SHIPPER'S REPRESENTATIVES HAD A BRIEF DISCUSSION WITH THE MARYLAND DEQ REGARDING THE EVENTS THAT TOOK PLACE. THE SHIPPER'S RESPONDERS HAD TWO CHEMISTS DONN LEVEL B PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT TO INVESTIGATE THE LEAKING DRUM. ONCE THE SPECIFIC LEAKING DRUM WAS DISCOVERED, IT WAS OVER PACKED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND IDENTIFIED AS LINE ITEM ON A MANIFEST. THE TRAILER WAS THEN REPACKED TO ENSURE THE INTEGRITY OF ALL DRUMS, LOADED, BLOCKED/BRACED WITH STRAPS TO PREVENT ANY POTENTIAL SHIFTING.
column169: THIS SHIPMENT IS BUILT AS A SHIPPER LOAD AND PLACED ON A PRE-SPOTTED TRAILER. THE RTS CUSTOMER IS AWARE OF THE RELEASE AND THAT A HOLE PROBABLY FROM A POWERED INDUSTRIAL TRUCK WAS FOUND IN A DRUM. THE SHIPPER IS TAKING STEPS TO ENSURE DRUMS IN THIS CONDITION ARE NOT LOADED ON FUTURE RTS EQUIPMENT.

column168: MOTOR VEHICLE ACCIDENT - VEHICLE 1 (CARRIER TRUCK AND TANKER) WAS COMING DOWN LOOKOUT MOUNTAIN HEADING NORTH ON OCHS HIGHWAY. VEHICLE 2, 3, AND 4 WERE HEADED UP THE MOUNTAIN TRAVELING SOUTH ON OCHS HIGHWAY. VEHICLE 1 CROSSED THE DOUBLE YELLOW LINE AND SIDESWIPED UNITS 2 AND 3. AFTER MAKING CONTACT WITH UNIT 2 AND 3, VEHICLE 1 TRAVELED DOWN THE MOUNTAIN A SHORT DISTANCE AND STRUCK VEHICLE 4 HEAD ON. THERE NO INJURIES IN VEHICLE 2 AND 3, HOWEVER THE DRIVER OF VEHICLE 4 WAS FATALLY INJURED. AFTER CONTACT WITH VEHICLE 4, VEHICLE 1 RAN OFF OF THE ROAD AND ROLLED OVER.  CHATTANOOGA POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENT ALONG WITH THE WRECKER COMPANY AND HEPACO EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. DUE TO THE NATURE OF THE LOAD WHICH WAS A CLASS 6.1 HAZARDOUS MATERIAL, AS A PRECAUTION, THE FIRE DEPARTMENT EVACUATED A FEW HOUSES DOWN THE MOUNTAIN FOR A SHORT PERIOD OF TIME. A TELEPHONE REPORT WAS CALLED IN TO NRC.  THE TRUCK AND TANKER WERE SUCCESSFULLY UPRIGHTED AND PULLED BACK ONTO THE ROAD WITHOUT ANY RELEASE OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.

column168: AT 4:00PM DRIVER WAS TRAVELING NORTH ON PURCHASE PARKWAY IN KY WHEN HE LOST CONTROL OF HIS TRACTOR AND WENT INTO THE DITCH. WITH THE GROUND BEING SATURATED HE COULD NOT RECOVER AND TRAVELED SEVERAL HUNDRED FEET BEFORE FLIPPING THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER ONTO THE PASSENGER SIDE THEN SKIDDING TO STOP. EMERGENCY RESPONSE TO THE SCENE CALLED OUR DETROIT OFFICE AND WE WERE NOTIFIED BY 5:00PM. DRIVER WAS TAKEN FOR EVALUATION TO THE MARSHALL COUNTY HOSPITAL AND ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION SERVICES HEPACO WERE CALLED TO AID IN RECOVERY.  THERE WERE NOT TRAILER LEAKS NOTED, BUT WHEN THE TRAILER BARREL WAS BREACHED FOR OFF LOADING CONTENTS, A SMALL LEAK DEVELOPED AT THE HEAD END OF THE TRAILER WHICH WAS CONTAINED AND NEUTRALIZED. THE NEUTRALIZED LIQUID WAS RECOVERED, THE TRAILER AND TRACTOR UPRIGHTED AND TOWED TO A GARAGE FOR INSPECTION. THE WORK WAS COMPLETED AT 4:00AM, THE ROADWAY REOPENED AND FINAL SITE CLEANUP COMPLETED. AFTER INSPECTION AT THE GARAGE A CRACK IN THE BARREL BEHIND THE FRONT END DOME WAS NOTED WHICH WAS CAUSED BY THE ROLLOVER AND BEGAN LEAKING AS THE VACUUM IN THE BARREL WAS RELIEVED.
column169: RECOMMENDATIONS TO PREVENT RECURRENCE INCLUDE PUBLICIZING THE ACCIDENT TO ALL DRIVERS, REFRESHER TRAINING ON ROLLOVER PROTECTION AND DEFENSIVE DRIVING.

column168: Truck was being loaded and a 55 gal drum of Tetrahydrofuran Dichloromethane was punctured on the side of the drum.  Employees immediately rolled the drum on its side to prevent further spillage.  Absorbents were placed down to contain the 1-gallon spill to the inside of the trailer. An environmental company was called to complete the cleanup.  The absorbents were worked into the liquid and swept up.  The absorbents, cleanup PPE and the leaking drum were placed in overpack drums and shrink wrapped.  They were stored on site for one day and disposed of the next day.  The trailer was ventilated overnight.

During a routine yard check, terminal personnel noticed hazmat dripping from the CMTV's internal valve indicator pins.  There was no noticeable hole or crack visible.  Due to the way the trailer was parked the release was not discovered until seven days after arrival.  They placed a bucket under the drip, called a cleanup contractor and transloaded the product to another CTMV.    The maintenance shop reported worn out internal valve o-rings.            Quality Event #68255.

column168: DRIVER OF TANK TRAILER STOPPED AT LOVES TRUCK STOP IN HUBBARD, OH.  UPON EXITING TRACTOR TRAILER PARKING AREA, THE TRAILER STRUCK THE TRAILER NEXT TO HIM AND CAUSED THE TRAILER LADDER TO COLLAPSE INTO THE TEMPERATURE PROBE, WHICH WAS PUSHED INTO THE TRAILER, CAUSING A HOLE IN THE TRAILER. THE MOLTEN CONTENTS THEN LEAKED OUT OF THIS HOLE ONTO THE ASPHALT PARKING LOT. THE REAGENT CHEMICAL DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED HIS TERMINAL MANAGER TO REPORT THE INCIDENT. A DIKE WAS SET UP TO CONTAIN THE LEAKING MATERIAL. THE LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONDERS ARRIVED ON SCENE SHORTLY THEREAFTER. CALLS WERE THEN MADE TO A LOCAL RESPONSE COMPANY, WHICH CONTAINED THE LEAKING MATERIAL BY WAY OF A DIKE AND, UPON SOLIDIFICATION, CLEANED UP AND DISPOSED OF THE SOLID ASPHALT PITCH MATERIAL.

column168: L3 FUZING & ORDNANCE SYSTEMS (FOS) RECEIVED A SHIPMENT OF EMPTY PACKAGING FROM GENERAL DYNAMICS-ORDNANCE & TACTICAL SYSTEMS (GD-OTS) ON 26 FEBRUARY 2018 GD-OTS RETURNED THE EMPTY PACKAGING TO FOS AS REUSABLE DUNNAGE UPON REVIEW OF THE EMPTY PACKAGING FOS DISCOVERED THAT ONE OF THE PACKAGES CONTAINED  A SINGLE M423 FUZE THE EMPTY PACKAGING WAS NOT SHIPPED AS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL, THUS THE PRESENCE OF A FUZE IN THE PACKAGING CONSTITUTES AN UNDECLARED SHIPMENT AS DEFINED BY 49 CFR 171.8 THIS INCIDENT DID NOT CAUSE OR CREATE THE LIKELIHOOD FOR INJURY PROPERTY DAMAGE CLOSURE OR ALTERATION OF TRANSPORTATION ROUTES OR ENVIRONMENTAL RELEASE THE SHIPMENT INVOLVED ONE SINGLE M423 FUZE WITH A TOTAL WEIGHT 0.0203 POUNDS OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. THE ITEM SHIPPED, WHILE UNDECLARED AS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WAS SENT IN PACKAGING CONFORMING TO THE COMPETENT AUTHORITY LETTER WHICH AUTHORIZES UP TO EIGHTY ONE (81) OF THESE DEVICES IN THE PACKAGING WHICH REPRESENTS AN ALLOWABLE TOTAL WEIGHT OF 1.6443 POUNDS OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.
column169: L3 FOS IS UNFAMILIAR WITH GD -OTS PROCESSES AND THEREFORE NOT ABLE TO MAKE ANY RECOMMENDATIONS FOR CHANGES TO THEIR  SYSTEMS TO PREVENT RECURRENCE

column168: AT 1410 HOURS ON FEBRUARY 27, 2018, RAILCAR  ACFX72866, A SULFURIC ACID LOAD, WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR AT THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCS) BEAUMONT, TX YARD. THE KCS ENVIRONMENTAL & HAZMAT DEPARTMENT DISPATCHED A RAILROAD QUALIFIED RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO ASSESS AND MITIGATE THE RELEASE.    UPON ARRIVAL, THE RESPONDER NEUTRALIZED THE ACID ON THE SIDE OF THE CAR SO THAT IT COULD BE SAFETY MOUNTED. ONCE ON TOP OF THE CAR, THE RESPONDER OBSERVED THE LIQUID FILL LINE FLANGE LEAKING. THE PRESSURE WAS RELEASED FROM THE CAR, STOPPING THE LEAK. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE FLANGE BOLTS THAT HOLD THE FLANGE TO THE TOP OF THE RAILCAR WERE LOOSE. ALL BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED TOOL TIGHT.    FILE NOTE: ITEM 19-THE QUANTITY RELEASED WAS ESTIMATED BASED ON THE BEST INFORMATION AVAILABLE AT THE TIME OF FILING. THIS SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED AS A ‘BULK’ SHIPMENT, AKA ONE CAR LOAD, THEREFORE THE EXACT AMOUNT OFFERED IN THIS PACKAGE IS NOT KNOWN TO THE CARRIER. THIS CARRIER DOES NOT HAVE ACCESS TO MASS BALANCE DATA WHICH CAN EXACTLY QUANTIFY THIS VALUE.
column169: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) NOTIFIED SHIPPER OF THIS RELEASE. NON-ACCIDENTAL RELEASES (NAR) CAN BE DEVASTATING ON SEVERAL DIFFERENT LEVELS. THEY CAN CAUSE PERSONAL INJURY, ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE, DISRUPT RAIL YARDS, ADJACENT FACILITIES AND COMMUNITIES, AND SNARL TRAIN OPERATIONS FOR HUNDREDS OF MILES AND BOTH DIRECTIONS. NARS ARE TROUBLESOME TO ALL BECAUSE THEY ARE, BY AND LARGE, PREVENTABLE. FOR NON-ACCIDENT RELEASE (A.K.A. PACKAGE CLOSURE ISSUES SUCH AS THIS), THE SHIPPER IS REQUESTED TO CONDUCT A ROOT-CAUSE INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE(S) OF RELEASE AND TO THEN FACILITATE CORRECTIVE ACTION TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. IT IS REQUESTED THAT THE SHIPPER SHARE THEIR FINDING WITH KCS. (PLEASE DIRECT YOUR ROOT CAUSE INVESTIGATION RESULTS AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TO STEVE MCNEALY, KCS RAILWAY, P.O. BOX 219335, KANSAS CITY, MO 64121. THE SHIPPER CAN REFERENCE HTTP://NAR.AAR.COM FOR HELP UNDERSTANDING AND PREVENTING NARS.

column168: DOUG, THE CHS DRIVER, CONTACTED AMY, AN EMPLOYEE AT LHC, TO VERIFY THE TANK INTO WHICH HE SHOULD DELIVER THE LOAD OF 11500 GALLONS OF CLEAR #2 DIESEL. AMY MISREAD THE TANK MONITOR AND TOLD DOUG THERE WAS PLENTY OF ROOM IN TANK #3, THE LHC TANK FARTHEST EAST IN THE CONTAINMENT. THE TANK WAS OVERFILLED AND ABOUT 50 GALLONS OF DIESEL WAS SPILLED INTO CONCRETE CONTAINMENT. DOUG IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN THE PUMP. THE REMAINING FUEL WAS PUMPED INTO TANK #1, THE TANK FARTHEST WEST, TOWARD THE ROAD. LHC USED THEIR VACUUM TRUCK TO REMOVE THE FREE PRODUCT FROM CONTAINMENT SORBENT PADS WERE USED, ADDITIONALLY CLEANING THE CONCRETE.
column169: THIS OVERFILL WAS SIMPLY THE RESULT OF HUMAN ERROR. THE LHC EMPLOYEE MISREAD THE TANK LEVEL MONITOR. THE DRIVER WAS TOLD TO DELIVER INTO THE WRONG TANK. THE BEST WAY TO PROTECT AGAINST A SIMILAR RELEASE IN THE FUTURE IS TO BETTER LABEL THE TANKS AND HAVE TO GAUGES THAT ARE VISIBLE TO THE DRIVER DELIVERING THE FUEL. THE ELECTRONIC MONITORS ARE CONVENIENT FOR KEEPING TRACK OF INVENTORY, BUT PROVIDE NO WARNING TO THE DRIVER THAT THE TANK IS APPROACHING MAXIMUM FILL LEVEL.

column168: Operator drove a forklift into the trailer to remove an IBC poly tote.  The lift was driven completely under the tote and the forks protruded out the opposite side.  The forks punctured a 55-gallon drum sitting on the opposite side of the tote.  The driver then lifted the forks to remove the tote causing a larger hole in the drum.  He began to reverse when he noticed paint draining down the trailer.  He set down the load reversed out of the truck onto the dock.  Absorbent was then applied to attempt to keep the material from leaving the trailer.
column169: Operators were trained on being aware of loads inside the trailers prior to unloading.  The purchase of absorbent material that is better designed to collect paint was staged in the receiving area.  Operators were trained on how to apply the absorbent to better keep the material from leaving the trailer.

column168: At 15:20 hours on Wednesday, February. 28, 2018 PTRA Job 150 reported product leaking from the top of ECUX 371013 while performing switching in PTRA North Yard. VOPAK Terminal, the shipper, was notified along with PTRA ER contractor Slick Response.  Slick Response arrived on scene at 16:15. The following is their write up of the incident:  2-28-2018    15:30 Slick Response received a call from Kirk with PTRA stating that they had a rail car located on track one at the North Yard that was actively leaking product from the top of the car. Kirk asked that we respond to the yard and make any needed repairs to the car and then clean the car after repairs were made.    16:15 Slick personnel are on location at this time. Upon arriving, Slick gained access to track 1 at the North Yr. After locking out the track and putting up the track flag. After securing the track, Slick personnel climbed to the top of the car where the product was observed coming out from under the dome lid. After removing the seal, slick raised the dome and observed the product coming from the 2” valve. Upon checking the bolts on the valve, Slick personnel found that all of the six bolts were less than finger tight and the valve was open approx. a quarter turn allowing product to escape. While in the process of tightening the bolts, Slick personnel noticed that as the bolts were being tightened, product started coming from under the valve around the four bolts that anchor the valve to the car. After tightening all the bolts, all the leaks stopped.    17:30 Slick personnel notified Kirk of the findings, he stated that Vopak were sending out a crew and for us to wait until they arrive to go over the findings with them.    18:00 Vopak on location at this time, Slick personnel are going over the findings with them, After going over the findings, Vopak personnel with to the top of the car to check the bolts. Upon comping down, Slick personnel went to the top of the car and began washing the exterior side of the car. Upon completion, Slick personnel released the track back to PTRA and are in route back to their shop.    19:30 Slick personnel are parked at the shop, and all equip has been cleaned , restocked and placed back into service.
column169: VOPAK terminal was notified and responded to the scene to investigate the cause of the leak. They are performing an internal investigation to determine the root cause of the loose liquid line valve assembly.

column168: On February 16, 2018, Source One Transportation driver of tractor tanker was filling up an aboveground storage tank, when it over filled and sprayed through the vent cap.Contractor estimates that approximately 25-gallons of diesel fuel has been released to the concrete and the side of the building. The contractor is working on pressure washing the side of the building at this time. Contractor indicated that a 30' x 50' area of concrete has been impacted. The contractor is utilizing absorbent materials to clean the release. The contractor has finished cleanup activities. Contractor generated (2) 55-gallon metal drums of the impacted absorbent materials to be taken off-site for disposal.

On February 23, 2018,  HOC Transport (REF # Springfield 1156) notified ERTS in regards to a gasoline release. According to the caller, the driver of tractor (9918) trailer (3854) was offloading gasoline into the underground storage tanks (UST) when the head popped off the hose causing a release. Approximately 300-gallons of gasoline has been released to the Speedway fuel island. The caller indicated that it is raining in the area and there are drains nearby. Contractor indicated that there is a representative from the EPA on site as well as the Fire Department. The Fire Department placed down absorbent materials and boom. The contractor indicated that the release has entered a storm drain. The contractor indicated that the EPA representative is trying to locate the outfall of the drain at this time.Contractor indicated that the drains outfalls were found and the EPA and the contractor indicated that the gasoline has been washed away. Contractor indicated that the outfall is approximately 0.5 mile from the site. Contractor used absorbent materials to clean the 20' x 150' asphalt parking lot. Contractor generated (3) 55-gallon metal drums of impacted absorbent materials to be taken off site for disposal. Contractor placed boom in the outfall as a preventative measure.

ON FEBRUARY 24, 2018, A RELEASE OF AN ESTIMATED 800 GALLONS OF #2 FUEL OIL WAS IDENTIFIED AT THE 115 WASHINGTON ST, AYERMA (PAGE HILLTOP SCHOOL). THE RELEASE WAS FIRST IDENTIFIED BY A LOCAL RESIDENT, WHOM NOTICED #2 FUEL OIL IN THE WETLANDS BEHIND THEIR RESIDENCE AND CONTACTED THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT. MASSDEP WAS NOTIFIED BY LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT. THE RELEASE OCCURRED AS A RESULT OF AN OVERFILL TO THE FORMER 6,000-GAL. UST BETWEEN FEBRUARY  22 AND 23, DUE IN PART TO THE FAILURE OF THE AUDIBLE ALARM FROM THE VEEDER ROOT SYSTEM ASSOCIATED WITH THE SITE UST. DELIVERIES OVER THE TWO DATES PUT ESTIMATED TANK VOLUME AT 7,400 GALLONS, WITH CONSUMPTION OF -300 GALLONS/DAY AT THE BOILER HEATING SYSTEM, LEAVING -800 GALLONS UNACCOUNTED FOR. THE OVERFILLING CAUSED OVER-PRESSURIZATION TO THE 6,000-GALLON UST AND ULTIMATELY CAUSED THE INNER AND OUTER WALLS OF THE FIBERGLASS UST TO FAIL. FUEL OIL THEN MIGRATED INTO THE PEA-STONE PACK SURROUNDING THE UST AND SUBSEQUENTLY ENTERED INTO AN ADJACENT CLAY-TILE DRAIN LEADING TO A LOCAL STORM WATER CONVEYANCE SYSTEM (SWCS) LEADING TO A CATCH BASIN (CB-1) LOCATED APPROXIMATELY 37 FEET WEST-NORTHWEST OF THE FORMER UST. FROM CB-1, OIL MIGRATED APPROXIMATELY 390 FEET WEST-SOUTHWEST THROUGH THE SWCS LOCATED ON WASHINGTON ST AND ULTIMATELY DISCHARGED AT AN OUTFALL LOCATION, #2 FUEL OIL MIGRATED NORTHWARD AND IMPACTED APPROXIMATELY 1,050 LINEAR FEET OF DRAINAGE BROOK VIA TWO UNNAMED STREAMS AND AN ESTIMATED 50,000 SQUARE FEET OF WETLANDS AREA. REFER TO ATTACHED PHOTOS, SALIENT BACKUP, DOCUMENTATION AND PLANS. MITIGATION AND CLEANUP EFFORTS HAVE BEEN PERFORMED UNDER MASSDEP RTN 2-20459, INCLUDING: REMOVAL OF RESIDUAL  FUEL OIL FROM FAILED UST, INSTALLATION OF TEMPORARY AST FOR SCHOOL TO USE UNDER PERMIT UST INTEGRITY AND ALARM SYSTEM TESTING, UST REMOVAL, OIL RECOVERY, GROUNDWATER EXTRACTION AND SOIL EXCAVATION AT TANK GRAVE, VENT STACK AND SWCS OUT-FAIL, CLEANING/EXTRACTION AND VIDEO INSPECTION OF SWCS, SOIL GROUNDWATER AND SURFACE WATER SAMPLING, REMEDIATION WASTE CHARACTERIZATION AND OFF-SITE MANAGEMENT, INSTALLATION OF NEW 8,000-GALLON UST, DEPLOYMENT OF SORBENT MATERIALS INTO THE AREA OF IMPACTS TO WOODED WETLANDS (I.E. DRAINAGE BROOK [S] AND WETLANDS), CONSTRUCTION OF TWO TEMP. OIL/WATER SEPARATORS IN WETLANDS, CONTINUED MANAGEMENT OF SORBENT MATERIALS, WETLAND FLAGGING AND RESOURCE BOUNDARY DELINEATION TO SUPPORT A NOTICE OF INTENT WITH MASSDEP/LOCAL CONSCOMM., PROVIDE NOTICES OF ENV. SAMPLING TO IMPACTED PROPERTY OWNER UNDER MCP, AND WORK OUT ACCESS AGREEMENTS FOR PROPERTY OWNERS OF DOWNGRADIENT IMPACTED PARCELS OF LAND.
column169: FROM THE DELIVERY PERSPECTIVE, DRIVERS WILL CONFIRM THE TOTAL STORAGE VOLUME OF A SUBJECT TANK AND THE VOLUME OF OIL THAT EXISTS IN SUCH TANK PRIOR TO CONDUCTING A TRANSFER. THIS WILL ALLOW THE DRIVER TO UNDERSTAND THE TOTAL STORAGE CAPACITY OF THE SUBJECT TANK AND THE VOLUME (GALLONS) OF OIL THAT THE SUBJECT TANK CAN SAFELY RECEIVE. THE DELIVERY CO. SHALL CONFIRM THE TYPE AND VOLUME OF OIL (S) TO BE DELIVERED TO A GIVEN TANK, AND VISUALLY CONFIRM THAT THE TANK GAUGE [S] INDICATE SUFFICIENT ROOM FOR THE DELIVERY. AS APPROPRIATE, THE VENDOR SHALL PERIODICALLY REQUEST INFORMATION FROM CLIENT (S) THAT PROVIDES DOCUMENTATION OF NECESSARY UST COMPLIANCE WITH 310 CMR 80.000.   FROM THE UST OWNER/OPERATOR PERSPECTIVE, THE PERSON (S) PRINCIPALLY IN CHARGE OF EACH TANK SYSTEM WILL CONFIRM THE TOTAL STORAGE VOLUME OF A SUBJECT TANK AND THE VOLUME OF OIL THAT EXISTS IN SUCH TANK PRIOR TO PLACING AN ORDER FOR DELIVERY FROM THE VENDOR. FURTHERMORE, THE OWNER/OPERATOR OF THE SUBJECT UST (S) SHALL ENSURE THAT THE SALIENT PROVISIONS OF 310 CMR 80.000 ARE FOLLOWED, INCLUDING APPLICABLE REQUIREMENTS LISTED UNDER DESIGN, CONSTRUCTION AND INSTALLATION; GENERAL OPERATING; LEAKAGE AND RELEASE; CHANGE IN PRODUCT, OUT OF SERVICE SYSTEMS AND CLOSURE.

column168: DUE TO SLIPPERY ROADS, A PASSENGER VEHICLE LOST CONTROL AND WENT INTO THE LANE OF OUR TRANSPORT, DRIVEN BY SCOTT PREYER. WHEN THE TRACTOR HIT THE VEHICLE, SCOTT LOST CONTROL AND SWERVED INTO THE DITCH ON THE OPPOSITE SIDE OF THE ROAD. THE ENTIRE UNIT DID A COMPLETE 180 AND ROLLED INTO THE DITCH. THE TRAILER SHELL SPLIT UNDER THE PRESSURE OF THE IMPACT, AND TWO COMPARTMENTS WERE COMPROMISED. FORTUNATELY, NO ONE WAS EVEN INJURED. EQUALLY FORTUNATE, THE JACKKNIFED TRACTOR SERVED AS A DAM TO CONTAIN THE SPILLED PRODUCT UNTIL WE COULD GET AN EXCAVATOR THERE. WE DUMPED A LOAD OF SAND ON EACH END OF THE ACCIDENT SCENE TO CONTAIN THE SPILL UNTIL OUR ENVIRONMENTAL VENDOR COULD VACUUM THE DITCH. THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER WERE REMOVED WITHIN 4 HOURS OF THE ACCIDENT ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP CONTINUED FOR THE NEXT WEEK.
column169: UNFORTUNATELY, ACCIDENTS HAPPEN HOWEVER, WE HAVE CREATED A RESPONSE PROTOCOL FOR FUTURE INCIDENTS IN ADDITION, WE HAVE PUT TOGETHER A RESPONSE TRAILER WITH OIL DRY, BOOMS, TOOLS, AND EQUIPMENT SO WE CAN IMPROVE OUR RESPONSE TIME.    SAFETY IS OUR #1 PRIORITY, SO WE ARE DEFINITELY USING THIS ACCIDENT AS AN EXAMPLE FOR PREVENTION TRAINING. OUR DRIVER DID EVERYTHING RIGHT IN THIS INSTANCE - HE DID NOT SWERVE TO AVOID COLLISIONS SO WE ARE FOCUSING ON HOW WE CAN BETTER REACT TO SPILLS.
