column168: DRIVER WAS S/B TENNESSEE ST IN THE #1 OF 2 LANES, AT THE POSTED LIMIT OF 35MPH (CONFIRMED WITH GPS), AND PACING A WATER DEPT PICKUP TRUCK WHO WAS IN THE #2 (CURB) LANE. WATER DEPT WITNESS STATED HE ACTIVATED WARMING LIGHTS AND SLOWED TO A STOP BEFORE TURNING RIGHT ONTO A STORMWATER, DRAINAGE ACCESS, AND WHEN HE LOOKED DOWN FROM HIS REAR VIEW MIRROR, THE TANKER WAS ROLLING OVER. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE TANKER MERGED FROM THE #1 LANE INTO THE #2 LANE AND IN DOING SO TRAVELED TOO FAR TO THE RIGHT, SIDESWIPING A PARKED CAR WHICH BECAME ATTACHED TO THE PASS SIDE OF THE TRACTOR, CAUSING THE TRACTOR TO TURN RIGHT SUDDENLY, JACK-KNIFING THE CARGO TANK TRAILER WHICH STRUCK A FIRE HYDRANT AS IT BEGAN TO ROLL OVER, BEFORE COMING TO REST UPSIDE DOWN ON THE PASSENGER SIDE OF THE SHELL AND THE PASSENGER SIDE VAPOR/ROLL-OVER PROTECTION RAIL. THE HEAD OF THE FIRE HYDRANT PUNCTURED AND BECAME LODGED IN THE SHELL OF THE CARGO TANK, WHICH ALLOWED 56 GALLONS OF CLEAR DIESEL TO LEAK FROM THE CARGO TANK AND ONTO THE GRASS, SIDEWALK AND SHRUBBERY BENEATH THE CARGO TANK. THE PARKED CAR ENDED UP ON TOP OF THE SEVERED FIRE HYDRANT AND WATER FLOWED DOWN THE CURB TO THE NEARBY STORM-WATER DRAINAGE. THE HAZMAT TEAM STABILIZED THE CARGO TANK TRAILER, INSTALLED A SAND BERM IN THE CURB AND CONTAINMENT POOLS UNDER THE DOME LIDS TO PREVENT ADDITIONAL SPILLAGE. FLYERS PROVIDED A TANKER FOR THE HAZMAT TEAM TO USE FOR PUMPING OUT THE OVERTURNED CARGO TANK’S CONTENTS. CA DEPT FISH & WILDLIFE CONDUCTED MULTIPLE SAMPLES OF THE WATER IN THE STORM-WATER DRAINAGE FOR TWO MILES DOWNSTREAM AND FOUND NO HYDROCARBONS PRESENT. ONCE THE TANKER WAS RIGHTED, THE CONTRACTED ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR BEGAN SITE CLEANUP AT THE DIRECTION OF FISH & WILDLIFE. 32QTY 55GAL DRUMS OF NON-HAZARDOUS WASTE WERE COLLECTED, 10 LIQUID FROM PRESSURE WASHING AND 22 FROM GRASS, SOIL, SHRUBBERY AND SORBENT MATERIALS.
column169: THIS INCIDENT WAS DISCUSSED WITH ALL OUR DRIVERS DURING OUR QUARTERLY SAFETY MEETINGS IN FEBRUARY. FLYERS TRANSPORTATION HAS RECENTLY SIGNED A CONTRACT WITH SMARTDRIVE SYSTEMS, A VIDEO INTELLIGENCE SOLUTIONS PROVIDER, TO INSTALL BOTH FORWARD AND DRIVER FACING CAMERAS IN OUR ENTIRE FLEET. THE LIABILITY COVERAGE IS GREAT BUT THE KEY SELLING POINT IS THEIR VIDEO SAFETY COACHING SYSTEM THAT WILL ALLOW US TO PRO-ACTIVELY COACH DRIVERS ON HABITS OR BEHAVIORS THAT WOULDN’T NORMALLY HAVE BEEN OBSERVED DURING OUR DRIVER RIDE ALONG OBSERVATIONS, BECAUSE THIS IS USUALLY WHEN DRIVERS ARE ON THEIR BEST BEHAVIOR.

column43: UNDYED ULTRA LOW SULFUR #2 DIESEL FUEL
column168: DRIVER DELIVERING DIESEL FUEL TO AST. DRIVER DID NOT START AT THE UNLOADING POINT DURING DELIVERY AND FAILED TO RECOGNIZE HIS OVERFILLING OF THE TANK THROUGH TANK VENT. APPROXIMATE DURATION OF OVERFILLED WAS TWO MINUTES. DRIVER ERROR CAUSED THE RELEASE.
column169: WE HELD A COACHING AND CANCELLING MEETING WITH OUR DRIVER TO RE-TRAIN THE IMPORTANCE OF STAYING AT THE LOADING AREA DURING DELIVERY. HAD THE DRIVER REMAINED AT THE POINT OF UNLOADING DURING THIS DELIVERY, HE WOULD HAVE SEEN THE OVERFILL ALARMS GOING OFF AND WOULD HAVE BEEN ABLE TO STOP THE DELIVERY OF PRODUCT BEFORE ANY RELEASE DUE TO AN OVERFILL OF THE TANK THAT FORCED PRODUCT OUT OF THE VENT.

column168: PACKAGE DID NOT FAIL. UNLOADING PIPING GASKETS FAILED DUE TO AGING OR DETERIORATION. EMPLOYEE NOTICED LEAKING WHILE UNLOADING 50% CAUSTIC SODA SOLUTION. ON-SITE EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM RESPONDED TO THE SPILL, AND THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS NOTIFIED. THE PUMP AND AIR PAD SUPPLY AIR WERE CUT OFF TO THE RAIL-CAR. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED, AND THE FAILED GASKETS WERE REPLACED. THE INVESTIGATION CONCLUDED 26.4 GALLONS WERE SPILLED TO THE GROUND.
column169: 1. REVIEW TYPE OF GASKETS BEING USED IN APPLICATION.  2. REVIEW ORIGINAL EQUIPMENT MANUFACTURER (OEM) RECOMMENDATIONS FOR GASKET CHANGE OUT FREQUENCY/EXPECTED LIFE.  3. INITIATE PREVENTIVE MAINTENANCE PLAN BASED UPON OEM RECOMMENDATIONS. 4. PERFORM FAILURE MODE EFFECTIVE ANALYSIS (FMEA) ON AIR PAD AND CAUSTIC CUT OFF POINTS TO ENSURE THEY ARE ACCESSIBLE DURING AN UNEXPECTED RELEASE.  5. INSTALL FLANGE COVERS ON EXPOSED FLANGES NEAR ACCESS PATHS AND POINTS.

column168: THE PORT TERMINAL RAILROAD ASSOCIATION (PTRA) WAS BRINGING IN A STRING OF 9 RAIL CARS INTO OUR TERMINAL. THE ENGINEER HAD NOT CONNECTED THE AIR BRAKES ON THE CARS TO THE LOCOMOTIVE. HE ENTERED THE TERMINAL TOO FAST AND COULD NOT STOP THE STRING; HE HIT AND DESTROYED THE RAIL STOP AT THE END OF THE TRACK, THEN BUSTED THRU THE 8” CONCRETE CONTAINMENT WALL AT THE END OF THE SPUR. THE BOTTOM OF THE RAIL CAR STRUCK THE WALL, PUNCTURING A HOLE IN THE INNER SHELL.  IT TOOK APPROX 5 HOURS FOR THE RAIL CAR TO DRAIN TO THE POINT IT STOPPED LEAKING. THE SPILL PRODUCT RAN INTO AN OUT OF SERVICE TRUCK SCALE PIT, WHERE IT WAS VACUUMED INTO TRUCKS, THEN OFF-LOADED INTO A TRAILER. NO RELEASE FROM THE FACILITY, NO RELEASE TO STORM WATER OUTFALL OF THE SHIP CHANNEL, OR INJURIES.  SEE ATTACHED PHOTOS.
column169: THE PORT TERMINAL RAILROAD ASSOCIATION HAS IMPLEMENTED AN OPERATIONAL PROCEDURE REQUIRING THAT THE AIR BRAKES TO ALL CARS BE HOOKED UP TO THE LOCOMOTIVE PRIOR TO MOVING.

column42: FUEL SYSTEM COMPONENTS (INCLUDING FUEL CONTROL UNITS (FCU), CARBURETORS, FUEL LINES, FUEL PUMPS)
column168: An automotive fuel pump for American Airlines Ground Service Equipment (GSE) was inadvertently shipped undeclared on American Airlines Flight 449 from PIT to PHX.  The Stores Materials Logistics Specialist (MLS) in PIT accepted the fuel pump from GSE but inadvertently failed to check to determine if the part was hazardous or not.  The fuel pump was packaged and shipped as a non-hazardous part.  Upon arrival in PHX, an MLS in PHX opened the box and inspected the part smelling fuel.  He reported this to his Supervisor who reported it to the Hazardous Materials In Transportation department who began an investigation.  There was no release of any fuel as the part had only residual amounts and was packaged in a blister pack and wrapped in bubble wrap, then placed in the shipping box.
column169: Better training is required to ensure parts are always checked to determine if they are hazardous before being shipped.  PIT Stores has instituted a procedure NOT to ship any GSE parts.  Further work is anticipated to determine if checking with Hazardous Materials in Transportation prior to shipping can identify hazardous GSE parts to develop shipping procedures around them to ensure they are shipped within Regulatory requirements.

Five cars derailed in the Pine Bluff yard.  Initial reports were of no releases however, a mechanical  personnel looked at a coupling and smelled a faint odor.  A contractor was onsite to remediate rice and  looked at the car and found that the liquid line valve was in the open position and the plug was less  than tool tight.  The vapor valve was closed but the plug was also less than tool tight.  The valve was  closed and the odor dissipated.  The car derailed all four trucks and onto its side with the housing at a three o'clock position
column169: Ensure the car valves and fittings are properly secured and ready for transportation before releasing the car for movement.

column168: An odor was detected by railroad personnel while walking next to this string of cars in track 42.  The  employee began short of breath, dizzy, and nauseated and was transported to a local medical facility. Upon inspection of the cars it was determined that the leak was coming from the vacuum relief valve. The valve was removed and a 1/16" Teflon blind flange was installed and the valve resecured.  Upon  re-inspection of the valve no odor or detection on the meter was found.  The car was placed in HZ waiting on the shipper to obtain an OTMA-3.  The liquid and vapor plugs were also less than tool tight with only one -two threads holding the plug. These were properly secured.
column169: Ensure all valves and fittings are properly secured and leak free prior to releasing the car into  transportation.  (NAR: 1125)

column168: REGULAR DAY PICKING UP MY LOAD AT 6:00PM. I LEFT AT 7:00 PM. IT WAS RAINING VERY BAD EVEN AT THIS POINT; IT WAS ALSO 20 DEGREES OUTSIDE. THIS CREATED VERY SLIPPERY CONDITIONS. AT APPROXIMATELY 1:00 AM I BEGAN TO EXIT THE HIGHWAY FOR FUEL AND TO END MY DAY. I ENTERED THE EXITING LANE TRAVELING 40 MPH. I WAS IN 8TH GEAR WITH JAKE BRAKES ON HIGH AS I HAD A LOAD THAT WAS AROUND 34 THOUSAND LBS. I WAS SLOWING AND APPROACHING DOWNGRADE OF EXIT WHEN MY GEARSHIFT POPPED OUT OF GEAR. I PUMPED MY BRAKES AND ALSO TRIED TO GET BACK INTO A GEAR SO THAT I COULD ENGAGE MY JAKES AS THE TRUCK WAS ONLY SLIDING NOT STOPPING. I WAS UNABLE TO DO EITHER, STOP OR SLOW DOWN MORE. AT THE END OF THE RAMP I WAS NOT TRAVELING AT 20 MPH AND TRYING TO COMPLETE AT TURN, AT THIS POINT TRYING TO MINIMIZE DAMAGE. THE TRAILER BEGAN TO SLIDE, I TRIED TO COUNTER STEER BUT HIT THE GUARD RAIL ON MY PASSENGER SIDE. THE TRUCK OVERTURNED AND CAME TO A REST ON THE GUARD RAIL. I EXITED THE TRUCK AND WALKED TO THE NEAREST BUSINESS TO MAKE NECESSARY PHONE CALLS.
column169: WE HAVE TAKEN PRECAUTIONARY STEPS TO IMPROVE DRIVER AWARENESS.
column172: Drum - fiber, metal or plastic not specified

AT APPROXIMATELY 1:00 AM I BEGAN TO EXIT THE HIGHWAY FOR FUEL AND TO END MY DAY. I ENTERED THE EXITING LANE TRAVELING 40 MPH. I WAS IN 8TH GEAR WITH JAKE BRAKES ON HIGH AS I HAD A LOAD THAT WAS AROUND 34 THOUSAND LBS. I WAS SLOWING AND APPROACHING DOWNGRADE OF EXIT WHEN MY GEARSHIFT POPPED OUT OF GEAR. I PUMPED MY BRAKES AND ALSO TRIED TO GET BACK INTO A GEAR SO THAT I COULD ENGAGE MY JAKES AS THE TRUCK WAS ONLY SLIDING NOT STOPPING. I WAS UNABLE TO DO EITHER, STOP OR SLOW DOWN MORE. AT THE END OF THE RAMP I WAS NOT TRAVELING AT 20 MPH AND TRYING TO COMPLETE AT TURN, AT THIS POINT TRYING TO MINIMIZE DAMAGE. THE TRAILER BEGAN TO SLIDE, I TRIED TO COUNTER STEER BUT HIT THE GUARD RAIL ON MY PASSENGER SIDE. THE TRUCK OVERTURNED AND CAME TO A REST ON THE GUARD RAIL. I EXITED THE TRUCK AND WALKED TO THE NEAREST BUSINESS TO MAKE NECESSARY PHONE CALLS.
column169: WE HAVE TAKEN PRECAUTIONARY STEPS TO IMPROVE DRIVER AWARENESS.

column42: ELEVATED TEMPERATURE LIQUID, N.O.S., AT OR ABOVE 100 C AND BELOW ITS FLASH POINT (INCLUDING MOLTEN METALS, MOLTEN SALTS, ETC.)
column168: ASPHALT CONTRACTORS DRIVER WAS RETURNING TO THE MONTGOMERY PLANT FACILITY, WHEN HE APPARENTLY FELL ASLEEP, CAUSING THE TRUCK/TRAILER TO LEAVE THE ROADWAY. THE TRUCK/TRAILER STRUCK A CULVERT WHICH CAUSED SEVERE DAMAGE TO THE TANKER. UPON IMPACT THE FORCE CAUSED THE MANHOLE COVER (FILL OPENING) TO RUPTURE AND POP OPEN CAUSING THE LIQUID ASPHALT TO SPILL INTO THE SWAMP AREA.   THE LIQUID WAS RELEASED INTO THE COLD WATER OF THE SWAMP, WHICH CAUSED IT TO SOLIDFY INSTANTLY. THEREFORE, THIS ELIMINATED THE FLOW OF THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL FROM TRAVELING DOWNSTREAM AND CAUSING MORE DAMAGE. MATS AND BOOMS WERE USED ON TOP OF WATER TO ELIMINATE THE FLOW OF DIESEL FUEL AND ANY OTHER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.   PLEASE SEE ATTACHED PHOTOS OF CLEANUP AND WRECKAGE.
column169: DRIVERS WERE TRAINED TO BE MORE AWARE OF THEIR CONDITIONS.
